This paper is likely to belong to the category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) as it deals with distributional semantics, which is a subfield of computational linguistics. It also involves natural language processing tasks such as semantic and syntactic tasks. 

It could also belong to the category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) as it involves a low-rank, weighted factorization of different PMI matrices, which is a common technique in machine learning. 

Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) is another likely category as the paper deals with improving the performance of distributional semantics models, which is a common goal in artificial intelligence research. 

Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) is a possible category as the paper involves manipulating and analyzing cooccurrence matrices, which are a type of data structure commonly used in natural language processing. 

Finally, Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) is a possible category as the paper involves training and evaluating models using various semantic and syntactic tasks, which can be done using neural networks or evolutionary algorithms.
